<p>We were asked to <a href="http://www.solede.com/blog/group-tours-to-italy/2015-09-28-educational-travel-how-solede-planned-a-complete-trip-to-italy.html?utm_source=blog&utm_medium=articolo%20blog&utm_campaign=Educational%20travel%3A%20how%20Solede%20managed%20to%20create%20an%20amazing%20trip%20to%20Italy">plan an educational trip to Northern Italy for a group of 40 American students</a> who wanted to know more of Italian economy and companies, since they were studying the field of economy.<br>After understanding all the requests of the foundation that contacted us, we planned an itinerary and the foundation was completely happy with our job, but unfortunately not everyone felt the same way.</p>

<p></p>

<h3><strong>HOW TO HANDLE CRITICS</strong></h3>

<p>One of the two professors who would have accompanied the class to Italy for 10 days had several critics to the itinerary we planned.<br>He didn’t agree in spending half the time in Milan and half in Modena as we proposed, since he would have prefered to sleep in Florence, Sirmione, Verona and Venice too. Sleeping in 6 cities in only 8 days sounded as a complete nonsense to us, since we had one small thing to take into account: time. Moreover, we were not planning a trip for a young couple travelling to Italy, but for a class of 40 students: transfers are inevitably slow, attractions you can see are limited by the group size and hotel managers don’t agree in making discounts for only one night at their hotel.<br>When we received these requests we knew that not all them could and had to be listened, or we would have been overwhelmed by thousands of other requirements, most of them unfeasible. On the other hand, we couldn’t simply get rid of those complaints, so we did our best to fulfil some of the requirements with the budget and time we had at disposal. <br>We managed to plan an even greater itinerary that took into consideration not only the professor’s needs, but also time for transfers and students tiredness.</p>

