<h3><strong>OPTIMISE TIME AT DISPOSAL</strong></h3>

<p>Following the new requirements, we decided to change the planned itinerary and make 3 main stops: Milan, Sirmione and Venice.<br>It was pretty clear to us that students wanted to see everything possible during their stay in northern Italy. In order to accomplish this task, we decided to optimise time, especially during transportation from one city to the other. <br>During their stay in Milan, students would have paid a visit to Modena, in order to visit the Ferrari Museum and also a balsamic vinegar company, which offers a vinegar degustation. Como was only an-hour away from Milan, and students would have spent the day relaxing and having fun on the lake shore. <br>During the bus transfer from Milan to Sirmione, students would have stopped to Pastrengo in the morning to visit the provider of paper-based packaging solutions, Smurfit Kappa. <br>Once in Sirmione they would have been able to take a day visit to Verona, only an hour away by bus, and spend the entire day in the city with a local guide to admire the famous Juliet’s balcony, the Arena and much more.<br>After their stay in Sirmione, they would have taken their bus to reach Venice: since hotels in Venice city centre were rather over budget, we opted for a hotel in the close village of Mestre, which turned out to be a good choice. In 2 days students would have had time to see the countless bridges of Venice, Piazza San Marco, Doge’s palace and even a glass blowing factory. We also planned a visit to the Peggy Guggenheim Collection in central Venice to admire the modern art museum on the Grand Canal.</p>

<p></p>

<h3><strong>THE FINAL APPROVAL</strong></h3>

<p>Once the revised itinerary was completed, it was submitted again to the foundation and to the professors. We were glad to know that they both agreed on the itinerary and appreciated our effort to include most of their suggestions. We obtained the final approval and started to organise the trip to Italy in every detail.</p>


